@node ReadMe "Very (very) important ALS notes..."
@{u}IMPORTANT NOTES@{uu}

» This archive contains Amiga ALS/ALS+/WB-ALS/InstallerALS, Acorn ALS/ALS+, FlexALS, MSX-ALS, Casio ALS and Databank ALS.  It does NOT contain the Spectrum, RM380Z, Amstrad or ALS Professional versions.
It DOES contain the necessary Amiga support files - ie. Spectrum.font, hisoftbasic.library and als.library

Apologies to pre-AmigaGuide 39 users - this text probably won't wordwrap for you... (oops)

1. @{b}MAKE SURE THAT @{I}SPECTRUM.FONT@{UI} (AND @{I}SPECTRUM/8@{UI}) IS IN THE CURRENT FONTS: DIRECTORY WHEN STARTING ALS.@{ub}
IF IT IS NOT, THE GAME WILL NOT RUN AND A BUG IN AMOS (ON THE A1200, ANYWAY), CAUSES A SCREEN TO BE LEFT OPEN AND SERIOUSLY SLOWS DOWN THE COMPUTER.
» This can be taken care of with the ALS-Install script - Double-click on the icon, make sure "Expert" is highlighted, then (after a few screens) click off ALS, ALS+ and ALS.guide.

2. @{B}MAKE SURE THAT HISOFTBASIC.LIBARY IS IN LIBS: WHEN STARTING WB-ALS.@{UB}  Fix as above.

3. Ctrl-C quits, and ALS can be pushed to the back (so you can get to any other programs running) with Left-Amiga-A. (WB-ALS can be pushed to the back using the normal method).

4. INSTALLATION:
  a) @{i}The easy way@{ui}
     Use the supplied Installer script - it will ask which versions you want to install, and where to put them.
     You need Installer, obviously, for this to work. I recommend getting the latest version from Aminet, as several recent scripts require it.
     
  b) @{i}The hard way@{ui}
     Just dump everything in one big directory.  Oh, except for Acorn !ALS, which needs to be on a PC formatted floppy, and the emulator versions (Flex etc), which ought to be in the same drawer as the emulators they're for.  The fonts need to be in fonts:, and the libraries need to be in libs:

5. The disclaimer bit:
THESE GAMES ARE PROVIDED "AS-IS".  AFTER EXTENSIVE TESTING WE HAVE DECIDED THAT THEY ARE FIT FOR HUMAN CONSUMPTION AND WILL NOT CAUSE SKIN CANCER.  ALL USE IS, HOWEVER, AT YOUR OWN RISK - EG. IF YOUR COMPUTER BLOWS UP, YOUR CALCULATOR CAN'T DO 2+2 (the answer is 5, by the way) YOUR HARD DRIVE GETS REFORMATTED, OR YOU LOSE AN ESSAY YOU'VE BEEN WRITING FOR THE LAST FEW HOURS, WE WILL ACCEPT NO RESPONSIBILTY.
If the messages at the end of the game offend you in any way (they shouldn't, unless you don't like being called a 'stupid little git'), it is also not our fault - this is a CONVERSION, remember? - we did not write the texts.  We do not have any connection with edited prefs files (well, not usually).

6. ALS versions included in this archive MUST be accompanied with this AmigaGuide file.  This AmigaGuide file must not be altered and should not be distributed without the executables.  The only exception to this is the Casio calculator version may be removed and distributed separately IF you include some acknowledgement that this is Unsatisfactory Software's code.  Casio are, of course, welcome to include this as an example listing in their calculator manuals!

7. @{"Click here for some last-minute WB-ALS notes..." link WB-ALS.readme}

8. The emulator versions obviously require a suitable emulator (see the individual notes for details), but if you have the required programs/knowledge then you should be able to transfer the files over to 'the real thing'.  The MSX version, in particular, should be reasonably easy to transfer.

9. @{u}Bugs@{uu}
The original ALS had several (two, no, three) bugs in it:
@{i}Bug 10@{ui}   - Sometimes a message would not appear at the end of the game.
@{i}Bug 'M'@{ui}  - Caps lock had to be OFF when mowing
@{i}Spelling@{ui} - Not sure about this, but I think 'relevant' was spelt wrong! (OK, not exactly important...)

These are gone from @{b}some@{ub} conversions, others have one, two or maybe all of them still intact.  Unfortunately, I can't remember versions...

10. A big thank you to Amiga Format for including loads of emulators on the Cover CD every month - if it hadn't been for you, several versions of ALS wouldn't exist. (I bet you're wishing you hadn't started that emulation feature now, aren't you?)

11. To anyone who wants to include Unsatisfactory's versions of ALS on magazine coverdisks, CDs etc:
Feel free! I would appreciate being notified, though - but this is not a requirement.

12. @{B}ALL CD compilers, please note:@{ub}
ALS+ needs to write to it's drawer, UNLESS the file 'Owner' is found.
If you want/need it to run direct from CD, please LOAD ALS+ FIRST, and make sure that there is some kind of licence information - set it to the name of the CD, or something.

13. Do NOT include ALS in commercial compilations - ALS is freeware, and considering that I am not making any money out of it, I don't see why other people should.
@{i}THE AMINET CDs ARE THE ONLY EXCEPTION TO THIS RULE@{ui}
@endnode

