@node MSX "The MSX (emulator) version"
This requires an MSX emulator (maybe MSX2), which is capable of handling MSX single-sided 'Virtual Disks' - fMSX 1.4 is the one I used to write this, and will now explain how to run ALS on it...
Load fMSX as usual, and select System... from the Settings pull-down menu.
The 'Drives' cycle gadget should be set to at least 1
Click on 'Load' to the right of the Drive A box, and select MSX-ALS.DSK from the requestor that appears.
Set ROM Type to MSX2 (I'm not sure if MSX1 will run ALS properly, as I haven't tried it - yet)
Close this window, then click on 'Reset'.  The MSX will boot into BASIC, and then (should) automatically load and run ALS.

· MSX Virtual Disk - contains file 'AUTOEXEC.BAS', which can be transferred on to a MS-DOS (with MSX bootblock) disk, through a suitable emulator if you want to use it on a real MSX.

Limitations:

· Makeshift 'graphics' again, as I don't know how to change the MSX character set - I suppose I could add an external font. (if I knew how)

· Colours - There appears to be no way of changing individual character's colours

· I can't figure out the graphics commands - I either get Syntax Error or Illegal Operation.  So no house.

· The MSX doesn't appear to have keyboard auto-repeat, so you have to press 'M' (lower-case only!) rapidly, rather than just holding the key down.

· There is no 'Quit' option... but you won't want to anyway!

WARNING · WARNING · WARNING
There is a bug in fMSX 1.4 which causes the settings to be saved on exit, even if you haven't set 'Save Preferences'.  Basically, this means next time you start fMSX, ALS will also start unless you manually remove it from the Drive A box.  The only way around this is to format a MS-DOS disk (and write a MSX bootblock to it), and copy AUTOEXEC.BAS from the virtual disk on to it.  You can then play ALS (assuming Drive A is now set to something like 'PC0:') by inserting the disk prior to starting the emulation.
@endnode

