@node RM380Z "ALS: Research Machines 380Z - version notes"
@{u}Special notes about the RM380Z version of ALS@{uu} (NOT INCLUDED ON THIS DISK)

Load the program ALS into RML Extended BASIC

1. @{i}There are no graphics whatsoever@{ui}
I could have used a version of "RML Extended BASIC" which had "High Resolution Graphics Level 2".  If the level 1 graphics were anything to go by, you could fit about 40×28 pixels on the screen (each pixel was the same size as each text character), and end up with three lines at the bottom for the actual game.  Actually, I've just figured out what No HRG Adaptor means - No High-res graphics.  That means I was talking about low-res.  I've also figured out the graphics commands, and positioning the cursor, so the game will be a @{b}lot@{ub} better now.  And there may even be graphics (but I doubt it)

2. @{i}There is no colour whatsoever@{ui}
No, it's nothing to do with Hi-res graphics Level 2.  It's because the RM380Z didn't have colour (come on, it was early-1980s - and you didn't get much for £1,000 - £2,000 those days).

3. @{i}There was a point 3 here, but I deleted it.@{ui}

4. @{i}There are less messages, and they don't scroll@{ui}
The RM380Z had 56K of memory (actually, I reckon it had 64K, 8K being used for CP/M and COS, because 56K is a weird amount) - not a problem, you might think.  And you'd be right.  The only reason I didn't put any more in was because, a) The updating was sooo slooow, that I didn't think anyone would have the patience to get to the end of the game [now speeded up], b) I didn't think anyone would bother to play it anyway, even if they could find it on the 5¼" disk I put it on (just emphasizing how rubbish it was - the computer, not the game), and c) I couldn't be bothered to type in any more, since I doubted anyone would play it more than once.
Now it's better, there is more messages.  But they still don't scroll.

5. @{i}The "mowing" key is different@{ui}
I accidently took out the code to check for a keypress, put it back in and forgot the bit which checked which key you pressed.  Anyway, it's more fun with it accepting any key, because you can pick the keyboard up and move it around, even pretend it's a lawnmower if you like.  That is, of course, if your RM380Z has a dodgy keyboard which sends random characters when you wiggle it around (like the one I was using).
However, to mow like the original you must use the "@{i}REPT@{ui}" key.

6. @{i}It has one of the features of @{"ALS+" link ALS+}!@{ui}
The feature in question is the "night-time" level.  Instead of trying to use the graphics commands to (hopefully) construct a house and sun, I decided to just print stars on the background.

Anyway, the point of creating a special RM380Z version was:

     a) There was no decent stuff to use on it (only a crap maze game and "a world of graphics on the 380Z" ... great)
     b) To prove that @{i}ANY @{ui}computer can have great games written for it.

Some of the lucky ones (that is, of course, people who haven't used a RM380Z) might be interested in trying my program "RM380Z".  It is the most accurate emulation of one you'll ever see (if only because no-one else has bothered to write one).  It's part of my Wierd/Pointless Programs Collection which may, sometime, be uploaded to Aminet.

(another) NOTE TO RM380Z USERS: If you want to obtain the RM380Z version of ALS then, I'm afraid, you're out of luck.  I saved the game onto the nearest available 5¼" disk which happened to not be mine (I don't own any, you see).  Anyway, the disk went in with all the other floppies and I don't actually know where they are.  Even if I did, I wouldn't be able to copy it onto another disk for you, because that means getting the RM380Z out.  Which happens to be in a cupboard.  And I'm not getting that heap of %@#! out just to copy a game over which you'll only play once.  It'll take me all day as well, since it's bound to lock up on me.  Anyway, if you're reading this file then you obviously own an Amiga (or know someone who does), so why not play the Amiga version?
@endnode

